quran[10]{c,v,t,f}:
27,89,"Whosoever comes with good will receive a reward better than his deed, {1} and they will be made secure from the terror of that Day.",footnotes:1:The reward will be better in two ways: (1) It will be higher than what a person will actually deserve for his good deeds; and (2) it will be everlasting and for ever though the good act was temporary and its influence confined to a limited period only.
27,90,"And whosoever comes with evil, they will be flung upon their faces into the Fire. Will you be recompensed for aught other than what you do? {1}",footnotes:1:That is
27,91,"(Tell them, O Muhammad): "I have been commanded only to serve the Lord of this city that He has made inviolable, to serve Him to Whom all things belong.<sup foot_note="179948">1</sup> I have been commanded to be of those that submit to Allah,",footnotes:179948:At several places in the Quran it has been stated clearly that an evil will be punished in the Hereafter only to the extent of the evil committed, but a good act will be rewarded much more generously by Allah than what the doer will actually deserve for it. For more examples of this, see(Surah Yunus: Ayats 26-27);  (Surah Al-Qasas: Ayat 84);  (Surah Al-Ankabut: Ayat 7); (Surah Saba: Ayats 37-38); (Surah Al-Mumin: Ayat 40).
  27,92,"and to recite the Qur'an." So, whosoever is guided, his guidance will be to his own good. As for those who stray, tell them: "I am none but a warner.""
27,93,"And say: "All praise be to Allah, Who will soon show you His Signs that you will recognize." Your Lord is not unaware of what you do."
28,1,"Ta'. Sin. Mim"
28,2,"These are the verses of the Clear Book."
28,3,"We recount to you with truth some parts of the story of Moses and Pharaoh {1} for the benefit of those who believe. {2}",footnotes:1:For comparison
28,4,"Indeed Pharaoh transgressed in the land {1} and divided its people into sections. {2} One group of them he humiliated, and slew their sons and spared their daughters. {3} Truly he was among the mischief-makers.",footnotes:1:The words ala fil-ard in the text are comprehensive and mean that he adopted a rebellious attitude in the land
28,5,"We wanted to bestow favour on those who were oppressed in the land. We wanted to make them leaders and heirs {1}",footnotes:1:That is
